# SigTekX - StreamingExecutor Memory Layout
# Layout: elk - supports self-loops for ring buffer advance operations
# Render: See docs/diagrams/README.md for rendering instructions
#
# This diagram shows the complete memory layout for StreamingExecutor (low-latency streaming mode),
# highlighting the ring buffer architecture, memory overhead, and data flow patterns for continuous
# streaming with arbitrary chunk sizes.
#
# LAYOUT STRATEGY (prevents crossing and winding arrows):
# 1. Invisible subgroups (input_flow, output_flow) - organize nodes into logical columns
#    without visible container borders (style.opacity: 0)
# 2. Ungrouped PCIe nodes - h2d/d2h float independently near their respective paths
#    rather than being forced together in a central container
# 3. Consistent top-to-bottom flow - ELK naturally routes connections cleanly

# Import shared styles
...@common/styles

direction: down

# ==============================================================================
# StreamingExecutor Memory Layout (Continuous Streaming Mode)
# ==============================================================================
streaming_memory: StreamingExecutor Memory Layout {
  class: streaming-green

  description: |md
    **StreamingExecutor Mode**: Low-latency streaming, arbitrary chunk sizes
    Total Memory: ~262 KB (nfft=2048, channels=2) **+60% vs BatchExecutor**
    Phase 1.1: Ring buffers in pinned memory — zero-copy DMA via peek_frame()
  |

  # Host Memory Space (organized in logical columns)
  streaming_host: Host Memory Space {
    class: host-memory-streaming

    # Input Flow Column (left side)
    # Note: Invisible container (opacity: 0) groups input-related nodes together
    # including ring buffers, staging, and pinned buffers for clean vertical flow
    input_flow: {
      style.opacity: 0

      host_input: |md
        **Input Chunk**
        (float*)

        - size: variable (arbitrary)
        - layout: per-channel chunks
      |
      host_input.shape: rectangle

      # Ring Buffers (nested within input_flow for proper grouping)
      ring_buffers: Ring Buffers (Per-Channel) {
        class: ring-buffer

        ringbuf0: |md
          **RingBuffer[0]**
          «lock-free»

          - capacity: 3 × nfft
          - write_pos: atomic<size_t>
          - read_pos: atomic<size_t>
          - available: atomic<size_t>
          - buffer: PinnedHostBuffer
        |
        ringbuf0.shape: rectangle
        ringbuf0.note: |md
          **Per-channel ring buffer**
          - Accumulates arbitrary chunks
          - 3× NFFT capacity prevents overflow
          - Lock-free thread-safe (SPSC)
          - Pinned memory for fast transfers
        |

        ringbuf1: |md
          **RingBuffer[1]**
          «lock-free»

          - capacity: 3 × nfft
          - write_pos: atomic<size_t>
          - read_pos: atomic<size_t>
          - available: atomic<size_t>
          - buffer: PinnedHostBuffer
        |
        ringbuf1.shape: rectangle
      }

    }

    # Output Flow Column (right side)
    # Note: Invisible container keeps output flow separate from input flow
    output_flow: {
      style.opacity: 0

      host_output: |md
        **Output Buffer**
        (float*)

        - size: (nfft/2+1) × channels
        - layout: magnitude (per frame)
      |
      host_output.shape: rectangle

      pinned1: |md
        **PinnedHostBuffer[1]**
        output_staging
        «page-locked»

        - size: (nfft/2+1) × channels
        - purpose: double buffering
      |
      pinned1.shape: rectangle
    }
  }

  # Device Memory Space
  streaming_device: Device Memory Space {
    class: gpu-memory

    dev_input0: |md
      **DeviceBuffer[0]**
      Input

      - size: nfft × channels × sizeof(float)
      - stride: nfft
      - layout: per-channel
    |
    dev_input0.shape: rectangle

    dev_input1: |md
      **DeviceBuffer[1]**
      Input

      - size: nfft × channels × sizeof(float)
      - stride: nfft
      - layout: per-channel
    |
    dev_input1.shape: rectangle

    dev_intermediate: |md
      **DeviceBuffer**
      Intermediate

      - size: (nfft/2+1) × channels × sizeof(float2)
      - format: complex (R2C output)
      - note: Hermitian symmetry
    |
    dev_intermediate.shape: rectangle

    dev_output: |md
      **DeviceBuffer**
      Output

      - size: (nfft/2+1) × channels × sizeof(float)
      - format: magnitude
      - layout: [ch0_bins, ch1_bins, ...]
    |
    dev_output.shape: rectangle

    window_coef: |md
      **Window Coefficients**
      «cached»

      - size: nfft × sizeof(float)
      - precomputed: true
    |
    window_coef.shape: rectangle

    work_area: |md
      **cuFFT Work Area**

      - size: dynamic
      - managed by: CufftPlan
    |
    work_area.shape: rectangle
  }

  # PCIe Transfer (ungrouped to prevent crossing)
  # Note: h2d and d2h are separate nodes (not in a container) so they can float
  # independently near their respective input/output paths. This prevents long
  # winding arrows that would occur if they were grouped together in the center.
  streaming_h2d: "H2D Stream[0]\n«PCIe Transfer»" {
    shape: rectangle
    class: pcie-transfer
  }

  streaming_d2h: "D2H Stream[2]\n«PCIe Transfer»" {
    shape: rectangle
    class: pcie-transfer
  }

  # Data flow - Streaming mode (subgroups prevent crossing)
  # Input path: Host → Ring Buffers → Direct DMA → Device (zero-copy, Phase 1.1)
  streaming_host.input_flow.host_input -> streaming_host.input_flow.ring_buffers.ringbuf0: "push(chunk[ch0])"
  streaming_host.input_flow.host_input -> streaming_host.input_flow.ring_buffers.ringbuf1: "push(chunk[ch1])"

  streaming_host.input_flow.ring_buffers.ringbuf0 -> streaming_h2d: "peek_frame(nfft)\nzero-copy span"
  streaming_host.input_flow.ring_buffers.ringbuf1 -> streaming_h2d: "peek_frame(nfft)\nzero-copy span"

  streaming_h2d -> streaming_device.dev_input0: "cudaMemcpyAsync\n(direct from pinned ring buf)"

  # Processing on device
  streaming_device.dev_input0 -> streaming_device.dev_input0: "window\n(in-place)"
  streaming_device.window_coef -> streaming_device.dev_input0: "element-wise\nmult" {
    class: dependency
  }
  streaming_device.dev_input0 -> streaming_device.dev_intermediate: "FFT\n(R2C)"
  streaming_device.dev_intermediate -> streaming_device.dev_output: magnitude

  # Output path: Device → Host
  streaming_device.dev_output -> streaming_d2h: async
  streaming_d2h -> streaming_host.output_flow.pinned1: cudaMemcpyAsync
  streaming_host.output_flow.pinned1 -> streaming_host.output_flow.host_output: memcpy

  # Ring buffer advance (self-loops)
  streaming_host.input_flow.ring_buffers.ringbuf0 -> streaming_host.input_flow.ring_buffers.ringbuf0: "advance(hop_size)\nafter frame"
  streaming_host.input_flow.ring_buffers.ringbuf1 -> streaming_host.input_flow.ring_buffers.ringbuf1: "advance(hop_size)\nafter frame"

  characteristics: |md
    **StreamingExecutor Memory Breakdown**:
    - Ring buffers: 3 × nfft × channels × sizeof(float) = **98 KB** (extra)
    - Device buffers: same as BatchExecutor = **164 KB**
    - **Total: ~262 KB (+60% overhead vs BatchExecutor)**

    **Tradeoffs**:
    ✅ Supports arbitrary input chunk sizes
    ✅ Continuous streaming capability
    ✅ Per-channel independence
    ✅ Zero-copy H2D DMA via peek_frame() (Phase 1.1)
    ❌ +60% memory overhead

    **Ring Buffer Operations**:
    1. push() - Add new samples (lock-free)
    2. peek_frame(nfft) - Zero-copy FrameView into pinned memory
    3. advance(hop_size) - Move read pointer (after D2H sync)

    **Capacity: 3× NFFT rationale**:
    - Prevents overflow during pipeline warmup
    - Allows safe accumulation before first extraction
    - Handles bursty input patterns
  |
  characteristics.class: note-gold
}

# ==============================================================================
# Comparison Note
# ==============================================================================
comparison: |md
  # Memory Layout Comparison

  ## BatchExecutor (Minimal Overhead - see 08_cpp_mem_batch.d2)
  - **Total Memory**: 164 KB
  - **Host**: Input/output buffers + 2 pinned staging buffers
  - **Device**: 2 input buffers + intermediate + output + window + work area
  - **No ring buffers**: Direct pipeline flow
  - **Use case**: High-throughput batch processing

  ## StreamingExecutor (+60% Memory - THIS DIAGRAM)
  - **Total Memory**: ~262 KB (+98 KB)
  - **Host**: Input/output buffers + pinned ring buffers (**98 KB**, direct DMA via peek_frame())
  - **Device**: Same as BatchExecutor (164 KB)
  - **Ring buffers**: Per-channel pinned memory — zero-copy H2D (Phase 1.1)
  - **Use case**: Real-time streaming with arbitrary chunk sizes

  Both modes use the same device memory layout and processing pipeline.
  The streaming overhead is entirely in host memory for ring buffer management.
|

comparison.class: core-blue
